<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="405" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="405">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="405">
The specific name &quot; 
<taxonomicName authority="Cameron, 1881" authorityName="Wang &amp; He &amp; Chen" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Sierola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sierola brevicaputa" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="405" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevicaputa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="405">Sierola brevicaputa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
&quot; is a compound Latin word of &quot; 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="405">brevi</emphasis>
&quot; (= short) and &quot; 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="405">caput</emphasis>
&quot; (= head) which refers to the head of this species wider than long.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="405" type="host">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="405">Host.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="405">
Larvae of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kusnezov" baseAuthorityYear="1916" class="Insecta" family="Cosmopterigidae" genus="Haplochrois" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Haplochrois theae" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="405" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="theae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="405">Haplochrois theae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Kusnezov, 1916).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="405" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="405">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="405">China (Zhejiang).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="405" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="405">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="405">This species can be distinguished from other species of this genus by having head about as long as wide, sides of head behind eyes rounded, pronotum distinctly sloping in lateral view, mesoscutum longer than mesoscutellum, and body light castaneous.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
